WorldFitness Database¶

Created by Roshan Cranford Luitel

The following notebook explains the creation process of a database using MySQL for a fictional gym called WorldFitness. As someone very interested in the wellness industry, I thought it would be interesting to get a better understanding of the systems in place that allow gyms to operate smoothly.

Tools Used::

  • MySQL for database creation
  • DBDiagram for ERD creation
  • Mockaroo for generating random data
  • ChatGPT for logo design
  • Google Colab for HTML creation

ERD Diagram¶

Below is a visual of the database structure for WorldFitness Gym.

Table Functions:¶

  • front_desk_log: Tracks member check-ins at the front desk.

  • subscription: Defines subscription plans available to members.

  • member_subscription: Associates members with their chosen subscription plan.

  • review: Stores feedback from members regarding their experience.

  • member: Holds personal information of gym members.

  • payment: Captures payment transactions linked to a member’s subscription.

  • fitness_class_session_attendance: Records which members attend each scheduled fitness class.

  • fitness_class_session: Represents scheduled sessions of a specific fitness class.

  • personal_training_session: Tracks individual personal training sessions between a member and personal trainer.

  • fitness_class_equipment: Records which gym equipment was used in a given fitness class.

  • equipment: Keeps an inventory of gym equipment.

  • employee: Maintains details about employees.

  • fitness_class: Lists all fitness classes offered by the gym.

Step 1: Create Database¶

The first step is to actually create the database and set it as the active database.

CREATE DATABASE WorldFitness;
USE WorldFitness;

Step 2: Create Tables¶

The second step is to create tables that will store relevant data for the gym's operations and specify the data types that they will be storing. The following code shows the creation process.

CREATE TABLE subscription(
    subscription_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    subscription_name VARCHAR(30) NOT NULL,
    subscription_description TEXT NOT NULL,
    monthly_price DECIMAL(10,2) NOT NULL,
    length_in_months INT NOT NULL
);

CREATE TABLE member(
    member_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    first_name VARCHAR(100) CHARACTER SET utf8mb4 NOT NULL,
    last_name VARCHAR(200) CHARACTER SET utf8mb4 NOT NULL,
    email VARCHAR(250) CHARACTER SET utf8mb4 NOT NULL,
    phone VARCHAR(15) NOT NULL,
    date_of_birth DATE NOT NULL
);

CREATE TABLE member_subscription(
    member_subscription_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    member_id INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (member_id) REFERENCES member(member_id),
    subscription_id INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (subscription_id) REFERENCES subscription(subscription_id),
    start_date DATE NOT NULL,
    end_date DATE,
    status VARCHAR(10)
);

CREATE TABLE payment(
    payment_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    member_subscription_id INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (member_subscription_id) REFERENCES member_subscription(member_subscription_id),
    payment_date DATE NOT NULL,
    payment_amount DECIMAL(10,2),
    payment_method VARCHAR(20)
);

CREATE TABLE front_desk_log(
    log_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    member_id INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (member_id) REFERENCES member (member_id),
    check_in_time DATETIME
);

CREATE TABLE employee(
    employee_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    first_name VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,
    last_name VARCHAR(200) NOT NULL,
    email VARCHAR(250) CHARACTER SET utf8mb4 NOT NULL,
    phone VARCHAR(15) NOT NULL,
    date_of_birth DATE NOT NULL,
    employee_position VARCHAR(75) NOT NULL,
    employment_type VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,
    salary DECIMAL(10,2),
    hourly_rate DECIMAL(10,2),
    hire_date DATE NOT NULL,
    employee_status VARCHAR(30) NOT NULL
);

CREATE TABLE personal_training_session(
    session_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    employee_id INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (employee_id) REFERENCES employee (employee_id),
    member_id INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (member_id) REFERENCES member (member_id),
    session_date DATETIME NOT NULL,
    duration_minutes INT NOT NULL,
    price DECIMAL (10,2)
);

CREATE TABLE review(
    review_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    member_id INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (member_id) REFERENCES member (member_id),
    rating INT NOT NULL,
    feedback TEXT,
    submission_date DATE
);

CREATE TABLE equipment(
    equipment_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    equipment_name VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,
    quantity INT NOT NULL,
    equipment_condition VARCHAR(30) NOT NULL,
    purchase_date DATE NOT NULL
);

CREATE TABLE fitness_class(
    class_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    class_name VARCHAR(70) NOT NULL,
    duration_minutes INT NOT NULL,
    max_participants INT NOT NULL,
    employee_id INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (employee_id) REFERENCES employee (employee_id)
);

CREATE TABLE fitness_class_equipment(
    class_equipment_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    class_id INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (class_id) REFERENCES fitness_class (class_id),
    equipment_id INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (equipment_id) REFERENCES equipment (equipment_id)
);

CREATE TABLE fitness_class_session(
    class_session_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    class_id INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (class_id) REFERENCES fitness_class (class_id),
    class_date DATE NOT NULL
);

CREATE TABLE fitness_class_session_attendance(
    class_session_attendance_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    member_id INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (member_id) REFERENCES member (member_id),
    class_session_id INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (class_session_id) REFERENCES fitness_class_session (class_session_id)
);

Step 3: Import Data¶

After creating the table structure and connections of the database, now it is time to actually fill in the columns with relevant data. To do this, I used the MySQL Table Data Import Wizard and imported the data table by table. In this process, I learned a lot about the importance of consistency between the data I was attempting to import from my csv files and the data types previously defined for each column of data.

Examaple of first 5 rows of fully populated employee table:¶

After populating each table with the gym data, there were a few columns intentionally left blank so that I could calculate their values and make the data as realistic as possible. The next few steps outline this process in detail.

Step 4: Calculate and update end_date and status columns in the subscription table¶

One of the columns left unpopulated was the end_date column in the subscription table. The logic behind this decision was that the end_date for a member's subscription was going to be based on their start_date and which type of subscription they signed up for (each subscription type is a different commitment length). The following code block looks at what subscription type was purchased by a customer and when they purchased it. Then, it calculates when the subscription expires so that the gym can keep track of when the next payment is due.

-- Calculate & Populate end_date
UPDATE member_subscription ms
INNER JOIN subscription s
    ON s.subscription_id = ms.subscription_id
SET
    ms.end_date = DATE_ADD(ms.start_date, INTERVAL s.length_in_months MONTH);

Another column left unpopulated in the same subscription table was the status column. The reason this was left unpopulated was because the status of the subscription would be based on whether the end date hasn't occurred yet. The following code updates the status column with "Active" if the end date is after the current date and "Expired" if it is before.

-- Calculate and Populate status
UPDATE member_subscription ms
SET
    ms.status = CASE
        WHEN ms.end_date >= '2024-12-22' THEN 'Active'
        ELSE 'Expired'
    END;

Step 5: Calculate and update payment_amount column in the payment table¶

Another column left unpopulated was the payment_amount column in the payment table. In order to make the numbers as realistic as possible, the following code block looks at what type of subscription each gym member has and determines how much they paid based on that subscription cost.

-- Calculate & Populate payment_amount based on subscription_id
UPDATE payment p
INNER JOIN member_subscription ms
    ON p.member_subscription_id = ms.member_subscription_id
SET
    p.payment_amount = CASE
        WHEN ms.subscription_id = 1 THEN 30 * 3
        WHEN ms.subscription_id = 2 THEN 40 * 6
        WHEN ms.subscription_id = 3 THEN 50 * 12
        ELSE 0
    END;

Step 6: Calculate and update price column in the personal_training_session table¶

The final column left unpopulated was the price column in the personal_training_session table. This price column reflects the total training session cost based on the personal trainer's hourly rate. In order to calculate this amount, the following code looks at the length of the personal training session in minutes, converts it to hours, and then calculates the total cost by multiplying the time in hours by the personal trainer's hourly rate.

-- Calculating price by multiplying duration (minutes) by gym hourly rate
UPDATE personal_training_session pts
INNER JOIN employee e
    ON pts.employee_id = e.employee_id
SET pts.price = e.hourly_rate * (pts.duration_minutes / 60);

Business Questions for Future Analysis¶

With this database in place, WorldFitness should be able to better understand what their gym is doing well and what can be improved. Below are a few business questions that this database can help WorldFitness address:

Revenue Performance:

  • What is the year-over-year revenue growth from membership fees?
  • Which subscription type brings in the most revenue and which type is the most popular?

Fitness Class Popularity & Attendance:

  • Which fitness classes are most popular?
  • How does fitness class time of day impact attendance?
  • Which personal trainers are the most popular among customers?

Front Desk & Customer Feedback:

  • What time of day is the gym most busy?
  • What do customers like and dislike about the gym?
